SENATE RESOLUTION 361
By McNally
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of James Harding Pratt.
WHEREAS, the members of this legislative body were greatly saddened to learn of the
passing of James Harding Pratt; and
WHEREAS, James Pratt was an exemplary public servant and consummate
professional who distinguished himself as an award-winning journalist, a top aide to U.S.
Senator James Sasser, and a government relations executive in the State of Tennessee; and
WHEREAS, born in Cleveland, Ohio, on August 13, 1954, to Joseph James Pratt and
Virginia Kendrick Pratt, Mr. Pratt moved to Memphis with his family as a child and went on to
attend East High School in Memphis and graduate from the University of Tennessee; and
WHEREAS, James Pratt joined The Tennessean as a copy desk editor, but his talent as
a reporter and writer soon caught the attention of legendary editor John Seigenthaler, who
ultimately assigned Mr. Pratt to some of the newspaper's toughest stories, including the Butcher
banking empire collapse series for which he won a National Headliner Award and the Bill Boner
investigative series, for which he and his fellow reporter Joel Kaplan received a Pulitzer Prize
nomination in investigative reporting; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his time as an investigative reporter, James Pratt served as a
city beat, business, and Capitol Hill reporter and a city desk editor; he left The Tennessean in
1989 to work for U.S. Senator James Sasser in Washington, D.C., first as his press secretary
and then as director of communications for the U.S. Senate Budget Committee; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Pratt joined the Ingram Group in 1995 and became a partner, and in
1999, he founded his own government relations firm, which is known today as Pratt Government
Strategies, Inc.; although he retired in 2017, the business is still family operated; and
SR0361
016644
- 1 -

WHEREAS, Mr. Pratt was deeply devoted to his family and always endeavored to
remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, left to mourn his memory and carry on his legacy are his daughter, Kendrick
Phillips Pratt; his former wife, Molly Leach Pratt; his sister, JoAnn Pratt Danna; his brother,
Richard Kendrick (Durenda) Pratt; and his nephews, Nicolas Joseph Danna and Richard
Kendrick Pratt, Jr.; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Pratt leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in public
life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, that we honor the memory of James
Harding Pratt, reflecting fondly upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to
living the examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Pratt.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy.
